<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911017-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>911017-0058.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- First Federal Bancorp:   Unit Is Put in Receivership;   New Institution Is Chartered</HL><DATE>10/17/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   FFS</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>CENTRAL U.S. BANKS (BAC)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   The Office of Thrift Supervision said it placed FirstFederal Savings Bank andamp; Trust, a Pontiac, Mich., subsidiary ofFirst Federal Bancorp Inc., in receivership and chartered anew federal mutual institution to take its place.   The new institution, First Federal Savings andamp; LoanAssociation, will operate in conservatorship under themanagement of the Resolution Trust Corp. The OTS said theinstitution and its 20 branches will remain open for businessas usual. First Federal Savings shareholders will retain nointerest in the new thrift, regulators said.</LP><TEXT>   First Federal Savings, &quot;had insufficient capital, with noprospect of replenishment without federal assistance,&quot;regulators said in a statement. The thrift had poor internalcontrols and deep losses on loans, according to OTS.   The thrift's earnings also were hindered by regulators'decision to exclude from capital $21.3 million in good will,a decision that First Federal Savings unsuccessfullychallenged in court.   First Federal Savings officials couldn't be reached forcomment last evening. As of June 30, First Federal Savingshad assets of $991.8 million. Net losses were $5.6 millionfor the first six months of 1991, after a net loss of $30.8million for all of 1990.</TEXT></DOC>